🎪 ON SALE NOW … The Circus is coming to town!

PuppetMaster 213 keeps Los Angeles fans happy with El Triste
@abc7la
Performing as Puppet Master213, Cain Carias created a puppet he named El Triste, which translates to The Sad One - the opposite of his own happy personality.

LOS ANGELES (KABC) -- When Cain Carias performs, his audience is mesmorized by the gentle movements and emotions he brings to his puppets.

Performing as Puppet Master213, Carias created a puppet he named El Triste, which translates to The Sad One.

The name, he said, was meant to represent the opposite emotions from his own personality.

"I'm always happy, I'm always smiling and I wanted to do something the opposite of that, which is sadness," Carias said.

Cain came to the United States from Tijuana when he was 13 years old. He said at the beginning it was difficult but then he was able to get his first job at the world famous Bob Baker Marionette Theater.
"As soon as I walked in there he just blew my mind," Carias recalled. "Because it was around Halloween so around that time they had skeletons that glow in the dark, they had Dracula, Vampira. It was a whole amazing thing going on so it really caught my attention."

He says Baker was his teacher and he fell in love with the art of puppetry. He now tries to honor the past while bringing a positive message for the future.

Bob Baker died in 2014 at age 90. Carias points proudly to a tattoo of Baker's name on his hand.

"I put the name Bob Baker here. He's the one that taught me everything that I know. This is actually a memorial for him and a reminder to myself that I'm going to be doing this forever because he practically saved my life. I grew up on the streets right here and it's not the best reputation that we have around here but we're putting on a different image for myself."

The organizer of an event where Carias recently performed says over the years PuppetMaster 213 has built up a following for his work and for El Triste. Now people want to take pictures with him and his puppets.

"Because PuppetMaster is so involved in the community and makes appearances at different health fairs and other different types of community events a lot of people are just really excited to see them🎭

BEYOND THE STREETS is pleased to announce Laugh Now, Cry Now, a group show curated by Ozzie Juarez.

Anchored by a stylistic range of storytelling, the show will feature the works of Los Angeles-based artists: 
Andrea Aragon, @aaragonb_art 
Andrew Durgin-Barnes, @aedbarnes 
Julissa Aaron, @not__urz 
and Isaac Escoto, @sickid1 

“This show is going to be special. The artists we’re featuring have this unique way of seeing the world through a lens that just came out of a pandemic, realizing things aren’t what we thought they were and just trying to cope with the new norm. It’s a distinguished observation of what’s happening in Los Angeles and the works are a snapshot of what’s going on in our culture, in society, and all the good and bad that’s transpired in between,” shares Ozzie Juarez. @ozziejuarez 

The opening reception for Laugh Now, Cry Now will take place on February 17, 2023 from 7PM to 9PM

Picture this… it’s a hot Summer evening on August 1, 1942, zoot-suiters were involved in a fight at a party near the Sleepy Lagoon. The next morning one of the said group of Zoot-Suiters José Díaz, was dead. What follows after in our beloved City of Angels can only be identified as acts of pure violence. On May 31, a clash between uniformed servicemen and Mexican American youths resulted in the beating of a U.S. sailor. Partly in retaliation, on the evening of June 3, about 50 sailors from the local U.S. Naval Reserve Armory marched through downtown Los Angeles carrying clubs and other crude weapons, attacking anyone seen wearing a zoot suit or other racially identified clothing. Turn to 80yrs later “to the date”Saturday June 3rd 2023 we will be honoring all those that were falsely imprisoned or lost their lives. Join us For the 80 year Anniversary of The Zoot Suit Riots Festival and Car Show. A classic car exhibition with vendors, Music, and community. Event is Free for all ages and will be held in our historical community of Little Tokyo. We are honored to announce our Grand Marshal and Guest speaker Dolores Huerta, President & Founder, Dolores Huerta Foundation. Dolores will be sharing our tribute to such an important time in our cities history. We stand United with our communities and feel it is important to recognize our past and share the stories. Join us for some Family Friendly fun for all and take in the local shops and eateries that make Little Tokyo Special. 🌹More information to follow🌹For any questions please email info@hellostranger.lasaturday June 3rd 2023 noon-6pm Corner of 2nd Street and San Pedro in Little Tokyo. Props to the organizers Manny Pachuco, Christina Romero, Pachuco Mark, Angela Romero for helping create this beautiful event along with our City Officials🌹 #siempre

But wait, there’s more!
Take a break, chat, and refresh yourself at a grilled cheese truck courtesy of Jason Segel and an ice cream truck courtesy of the Henson Company!

Bring your puppets, your friends, and your enthusiastic self from 10am until noon! More details below!

Event Details:
Date: Friday Sept. 22nd
Time: 10am - Noon
Location: Paramount Studio, Windsor Gate 5433 Melrose Ave. 90038

When you get there, please check in. Members bring your id’s. SAG-AFTRA check in is across the street from the Windsor gate and WGA check in is on the East side of the Windsor Gate. 

Bring a puppet, but SAG- AFTRA has kindly requested that puppets representing struck work not be present at the picket. 

Having four-legged friends on the picket lines is fun, but due to the extreme heat and volume of picketers, we recommend leaving your dogs at home for their safety.

We look forward to seeing you, standing shoulder to shoulder and puppet to puppet as we fight for a fair contract.

In Solidarity!

Up next in uplifting folks who are part of Levitt LA's success is Mario Fuentes. He is the owner of the 20+ year old local business Ricky's Pizza that's right down the street from MacArthur Park, they also opened up a 2nd location in East LA earlier this year. 

Mario's also lead singer of one of our favorite reggae-ska bands Blanco y Negro! They've played gigs to help collect gifts for local youth and when we needed to do a full dress rehearsal to get ready for the 2022 season. Check out their new song "Hola Señorita" and follow them to stay updated on their upcoming shows.

Thank you for making some incredible pizza and music Mario! Support your local businesses and musicians.

The work of Levitt LA is made possible by donors like you. Make your end of year tax deductible donation today via the link in our bio. Thank you to all who've contributed this year and years past to keep the concerts in MacArthur Park going!

El siguiente persona que es parte del éxito de Levitt LA es Mario Fuentes. Él es el propietario del negocio local Ricky's Pizza, de más de 20 años en la comunidad que está cerca de MacArthur Park. También abrieron una segunda ubicación en East LA a principios de este año.

¡Mario también es el cantante principal de una de nuestras bandas favoritas de reggae-ska, Blanco y Negro! Han realizado conciertos para ayudar a recolectar regalos para los jóvenes locales y cuando necesitábamos hacer un ensayo general para prepararnos para la temporada 2022. Escucha su nueva canción "Hola Señorita" y síguelos para mantenerte actualizado sobre sus próximos shows.

¡Gracias por hacer una pizza y música increíbles, Mario! Apoye a sus empresas y músicos locales.

El trabajo de Levitt LA es posible gracias a donantes como usted. Haga hoy su donación deducible de impuestos de fin de año a través del enlace en nuestra biografía. ¡Gracias a todos los que han contribuido este año y los años anteriores para que los conciertos en MacArthur Park sigan adelante!
